<div id="review_406499112" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/406499112" />
    <a title="Daniel Roy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5368477-daniel-roy"><img alt="Daniel Roy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513163643p2/5368477.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/406499112?book_show_action=true">Sep 03, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Daniel Roy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Daniel Roy" href="/user/show/5368477-daniel-roy">Daniel Roy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/15729014-the-lions-of-al-rassan">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5368477-daniel-roy?shelf=taw-bookclub">taw-bookclub</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5368477-daniel-roy?shelf=sf">sf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5368477-daniel-roy?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5368477-daniel-roy?shelf=abandoned">abandoned</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer406499112" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13411062981492930580">I usually have a rule that if a book doesn&apos;t grab my attention within 50 pages, I just drop it and move on. Too many great books, not enough time. I gave <i>The Lions of Al-Rassan</i> a good chance with 150 pages, and it still utterly failed to grab me. Maybe it was a bad idea to read a high-minded historical fantasy epic right after <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/140671.The_Black_Company' title='The Black Company by Glen Cook' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Black Company</a>. Or maybe I&apos;m too old and grumpy for bombastic opera-like fantasies. Maybe <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13496.A_Game_of_Thrones__A_Song_of_Ice_and_Fire___1_' title='A Game of Thrones (A Song of Ice and Fire, #1) by George R.R. Martin' rel='nofollow noopener'>A Game of Thrones</a> has made fantasy unpalatable unless it features a threshold </span>
  <span id="freeText13411062981492930580" style="display:none">I usually have a rule that if a book doesn't grab my attention within 50 pages, I just drop it and move on. Too many great books, not enough time. I gave <i>The Lions of Al-Rassan</i> a good chance with 150 pages, and it still utterly failed to grab me. Maybe it was a bad idea to read a high-minded historical fantasy epic right after <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/140671.The_Black_Company" title="The Black Company by Glen Cook" rel="nofollow noopener">The Black Company</a>. Or maybe I'm too old and grumpy for bombastic opera-like fantasies. Maybe <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13496.A_Game_of_Thrones__A_Song_of_Ice_and_Fire___1_" title="A Game of Thrones (A Song of Ice and Fire, #1) by George R.R. Martin" rel="nofollow noopener">A Game of Thrones</a> has made fantasy unpalatable unless it features a threshold amount of scars and realpolitik. I dunno.<br /><br />All I know is, I neither care for the style nor for the characters. The prose felt to me like what a 15 year-old boy would find amazing. It's full of semi-clever turns of phrases and descriptions, but it still drips with dialog adverbs. And man, it's so bloody high-minded. The author uses the word 'congress' to describe fucking, for crying out loud.<br /><br />The setting bugs me. I know it's historical fantasy. But see, when <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/346732.George_R_R__Martin" title="George R.R. Martin" rel="nofollow noopener">George R.R. Martin</a> strips medieval Europe of its specifics for the purpose of creating a fantasy world, he replaces the cultural details he takes out with some appealing details of his own. But <i>The Lions of Al-Rassan</i> is just stripped down, diluted Moorish Spain. You can tell right away who are the Jews, the Arabs, and the Christians, except that they're from an alternate universe where everything lacks detail and texture. Gone is the aesthetics of Islam, for instance, or the gravitas of Jewish history. Instead we get Kindath waxing poetic about how it sucks to be a wandering people.<br /><br />The characters never pulled me in. They're all suitably noble yet mischievous, and the women are appropriately strong and independent despite living as second-class citizens. It's just all so pat. They feel like the vanilla ice cream of fantasy protagonists.<br /><br />My only regret in dropping this book early is that I won't get to witness the magnificence of the intercultural bromance at the heart of this book. Ah well. I'm sure it was filled with just the right amount of drama and yearning.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13411062981492930580" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


